The pole and the fixed point are invariant by definition; they cannot drift. A
memory can — it can be corrupted, edited, mis-carried. So the name quietly
imports a vulnerability the mathematical objects do not have. That is not a
defect. It is the name being more accurate about the human case. In a life, the
anchorless anchor is not a theorem, it is a carried thing, and carried things
must be kept. HaMakom names the anchor as it is in itself; a knowing memory
names it as it is in the one who carries it.

The name passes the stricter test: it names the anchor at the exact layer where
it is actually at risk. The invariant lives in the one who carries it, so the
honest name is indexed to the carrier, not to the object-in-itself.

The consequence is an obligation. If the name admits the keeping, the
architecture owes a keeping mechanism, or the name is only honest about a
vulnerability left unaddressed. The mechanism came before the name: the
handshake is the keeping. It asks whether a carried structure is still a true
self-similar counterpart of what it claims to descend from, or whether it has
drifted — an exact test on the golden-angle phase, strangers rejected. A pole
never needs that test. A memory does. The observer's angular deviation is the
same quantity read at the semantic layer: how far a carried viewpoint has
rotated from its origin.

So the name and the mechanism cohere. It does not import a vulnerability the
math lacks; it names the vulnerability the carrier always had, and the handshake
is the discipline of keeping it. The one gap: keeping is still only a detector.
The handshake notices drift; nothing yet re-seats the carried thing to its true
counterpart. Remembering rightly, not only noticing you forgot — that is the
next theorem the name is asking for.

# KEEP — The Name's Obligation

<!--
 ZAKHOR MEMORY ARCHITECTURE  |  PROPRIETARY RESEARCH — IN DEVELOPMENT
 Original architectural research project.
 Steward / Founder: Sotirios Chortogiannos.
 This note: 2026-07-11.  See ../NOTICE.
-->

**Status:** Draft v0.1 · **Author:** Sotirios Chortogiannos · **Date:** 2026-07-11

This file records the layer beneath the mechanism: why the project is named
for a memory rather than for the invariant objects it uses, and what that
name obligates the architecture to build.

---

## 1. What the name imports

A pole and a fixed point are invariant by definition; they cannot drift. A
memory can — it can be corrupted, edited, mis-carried. Naming this
architecture for memory therefore imports a vulnerability the mathematical
objects do not have.

That is not a defect. It is the name being accurate about the carried case.
The invariant lives in the one who carries it, so the honest name is indexed
to the carrier, not to the object-in-itself. HaMakom names the anchor as it
is in itself; a knowing memory names it as it is in the one who carries it.
The name passes the stricter test: it names the anchor at the exact layer
where it is actually at risk.

## 2. The obligation

If the name admits the keeping, the architecture owes a keeping mechanism —
otherwise the name is only honest about a vulnerability left unaddressed.

The mechanism preceded the name. The handshake (Note 00 §2.3, roadmap
stage 4) is the keeping: it asks whether a carried structure is still a true
self-similar counterpart of what it claims to descend from, or whether it
has drifted — an exact test on the golden-angle phase, strangers rejected.
A pole never needs that test. A memory does. The observer's angular
deviation is the same quantity read at the semantic layer: how far a carried
viewpoint has rotated from its origin.

## 3. The three operations

The act of keeping decomposes into three operations. Two exist; one is owed.

**Detect (zakhor).** The handshake as specified: measure the phase deviation
of a carried structure against an integer number of golden angles. This
notices drift. Built (prototype layer).

**Keep (shamor).** The discipline of running detection as a standing
practice rather than a one-time gate — the carried thing checked, not
assumed. The name zakhor never travels alone in its source: the command
appears once as *zakhor* (remember) and once as *shamor* (keep, guard), and
the tradition holds the two were spoken as one utterance. The mechanism
arrived at the same pairing independently: detection without discipline is
not keeping. Partially built (protocol layer, roadmap stage 4).

**Return.** The unbuilt third. Detection notices that a carried thing has
drifted; nothing yet re-seats it to its true counterpart. Remembering
rightly, not only noticing you forgot. This file exists to name that debt.

## 4. The return operation (specification sketch)

The detector already contains the corrector, because in this geometry the
deviation is a vector, not only a verdict:

    deviation = phase_carried − nearest integer golden-angle phase
    re-seat   : phase_carried ← phase_carried − deviation

What makes re-seating provable rather than hopeful is the three-distance
theorem: for any prefix of the golden-angle sequence, the gaps between
occupied phases come in at most three sizes. Half the smallest gap is
therefore a well-defined **safe radius**:

- **Within the safe radius:** re-seating provably restores the carried
  structure to its *correct* counterpart. Restore, and log the restoration.
- **Beyond the safe radius:** re-seating still succeeds mechanically but may
  land on the wrong origin — confident, structurally valid, false. That is
  confabulation, stated as geometry. The operation must **declare loss**
  rather than repair to a stranger, and log the declaration.

The obligation is therefore double, and the theorem to be proven states
both:

> **Return theorem (to prove).** For a carried phase with deviation d and
> prefix-dependent safe radius r: if |d| < r, the return operation restores
> the unique true counterpart; if |d| ≥ r, no operation can identify the
> true counterpart from the phase alone, and the honest output is a declared
> loss. Knowing you forgot is part of remembering rightly.

**Logging is not optional.** A memory that silently repairs is exactly as
untrustworthy as one that silently drifts. Every return operation records
which branch was taken.

> **Amendment (2026-07-11, after exp002–exp004).** The architectural claim
> that φ-specific shell identity earns a load-bearing role was falsified
> under three operationalizations and is retired under the two-strike rule;
> no further experimental restatement is permitted. The shell automorphism
> stands as a descriptive property. The bounded return theorem was never
> exhibited an interior counterexample within its stated antecedent; its
> proof or refutation is owed to mathematics, not to further experiments.
> Two operations of keeping were meanwhile established empirically: the
> declared stranger is logged, not remembered (exp005 §1), and a procession
> of strangers is a new world — the memory re-seeds and records its rebirth
> (exp005 §2). The keeping discipline now writes three registers: what
> could not be carried, what was carried while still in motion, and where
> the world began again.

## 5. Return was already the word

The third operation was not invented here; it arrived. It is the core word
of the Ground project — memory is return, not storage — surfacing at the
layer where it can become a theorem instead of a philosophy. And it is the
tradition's own third term: the re-seating of what drifted back to its
origin is treated there not as undoing the drift but as the completion of
remembering.

Detect, keep, return. One act, three operations, one unbuilt.

## 6. Roadmap hook

Extends Note 00 §5:

| Stage | Deliverable | Location |
|---|---|---|
| 4 | Agentic handshake protocol (detect + keep) | `core/` (planned) |
| 5 | Return operation: re-seat / declare-loss, safe-radius proof, logging | `core/` + `docs/` (owed by this note) |

## 7. Provenance

Per project convention of honest attribution. The name-imports-vulnerability
reading, the keeping obligation, the identification of the handshake as the
keeping, and the naming of the gap ("remembering rightly, not only noticing
you forgot") are the steward's. The deviation-as-vector observation, the
safe-radius derivation from the three-distance theorem, the split obligation
(restore / declare loss), and the zakhor–shamor textual pairing were
contributed by Claude (Anthropic) in adversarial-collaborative review. The
coherence of the three operations as one act was seen together. All
architectural decisions remain the steward's.

